Until yesterday, even for a meaningful number of Capitol Hill insiders, for=
mer congressman Tim Walz was not exactly a known quantity on the national s=
tage. Of course, now that Kamala Harris has selected the amiable everyman g=
overnor from Minnesota as her running mate, Walz has become, overnight, one=
 of the most scrutinized public figures in America. So far, he=E2=80=99s me=
t the moment, offering up a folksy but smartly honed speech on Tuesday nigh=
t, alongside Harris, in which he deftly skewered his political foil, J.D. V=
ance.

In this conversation, adapted from Puck=E2=80=99s daily The Powers That Be =
podcast, Peter Hamby and John Heilemann chew over the most pertinent questi=
ons surrounding Walz: Where the hell did he come from, what does he really =
add to the ticket, what the pick really says about Harris
and her campaign strategy, and much more=E2=80=A6

The Dark Horse

Peter Hamby: John, I have to ask you, and you have to be honest with me: Ho=
w familiar were you with Tim Walz before two weeks ago?

John Heilemann: I was just on television with former senator Claire McCaski=
ll, who said, =E2=80=9CI wasn=E2=80=99t really very familiar with him,=E2=
=80=9D which is Claire=E2=80=99s way of saying, =E2=80=9CI had no idea who =
he was.=E2=80=9D And Claire is pretty well-versed. Walz is a six-term congr=
essman from Minnesota, and now governor, and the main national story he was=
 ever at the center of=E2=80=94and he wasn=E2=80=99t even at the center of =
it=E2=80=94was the George Floyd story. So I=E2=80=99m just like Claire McCa=
skill: I knew who he was, I could have picked him out of a lineup, but if y=
ou=E2=80=99d asked me to rate his political athleticism, I would have been =
like, =E2=80=9CSorry, I haven=E2=80=99t seen enough to
know.=E2=80=9D

He genuinely came out of nowhere. It=E2=80=99s interesting to see people fr=
om the Midwest and from Minnesota who know him, or who claim to know him, b=
eing like, =E2=80=9CNow the world gets to see what we=E2=80=99ve all known!=
=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m like, How the hell did we miss this? He was on Capito=
l Hill for so long.

Someone I know sent me an email=E2=80=94someone who=E2=80=99s not famous, b=
ut a name in the last 30 years in Democratic circles in Washington=E2=80=94=
and she said Walz had been her dark horse candidate. And she went on to say=
, =E2=80=9CBecause my nephew ran twice for his seat in Minnesota and I got =
to see him in action.=E2=80=9D She always thought he would be perfect for t=
his. So there are people in the Midwest who do have this view. I bet if we =
had Amy Klobuchar on here, she would tell you Tim Walz stories till the cow=
s came home. But for me, it was really a jolt to the solar plexus.

What got me was, on one of his early hits on Morning Joe, he was
riffing on why J.D. Vance didn=E2=80=99t know rural America, and he said, =
=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know, I got a lot of hillbilly nephews, and none o=
f them went to Yale.=E2=80=9D And I thought that was a really good line, a =
good piece of political communication from a couple different angles. His v=
ernacular, that kind of Main Street America, and the way he deploys it=E2=
=80=A6 just like Hubert Humphrey, the happy warrior, he=E2=80=99s smiling w=
hile he takes the truncheon out and applies it to your cranium, and next th=
ing, you=E2=80=99re out. That=E2=80=99s a real skill.

It=E2=80=99s a powerful line to deploy, especially from a guy in a party cu=
rrently ruled by college-educated voters. That=E2=80=99s the electorate for=
 Democrats in a lot of ways, along with Black voters. A lot of the electeds=
, including someone who was passed over for the slot, Josh Shapiro, are law=
yers who went to nice schools. And Walz is a public school kid=E2=80=94he w=
ent to school on the G.I. Bill, just like Vance. I think that=E2=80=99s one
reason they decided to pick him, because his framing against Vance plays we=
ll for them.

That=E2=80=99s 100 percent right. And not only as a public school kid, but =
a public school teacher. My father=E2=80=99s family was from Wisconsin, my =
mother=E2=80=99s family was from the Upper Peninsula of Michigan. If you=E2=
=80=99re in those worlds, a liberal librarian or a liberal school teacher i=
s a common trope. They=E2=80=99re not seen as threatening liberals. They=E2=
=80=99re not woke. So Walz is a very familiar figure, in the tradition of R=
epublican progressivism in Wisconsin, like Robert La Follette, before we go=
t to the Trump era. It was like, =E2=80=9COh, you know, he=E2=80=99s not re=
ally my cup of tea, but he=E2=80=99s not trying to impose some woke ideolog=
y on my kids.=E2=80=9D He=E2=80=99s a throwback in that way.

I think part of the way this pick works, in terms of the internal politics =
of the Democratic Party, is that his policies are fine for A.O.C. or anybod=
y on the Squad,
but he does not read Squad in the cultural sense in America. He reads like =
a guy you=E2=80=99d run into at Pep Boys when you=E2=80=99re buying a new m=
uffler. And you=E2=80=99re like, =E2=80=9COh, does he know how to fix my ca=
r?=E2=80=9D And that=E2=80=99s a good place to be.

And then there was the way the Democratic Party, the electeds, coalesced ar=
ound him and came out=E2=80=94A.O.C. and Bernie and Terry McAuliffe and Joe=
 Manchin. One reason Democrats are excited about Kamala is that she seems l=
ike she cares about winning, totally papering over all of her issues that s=
he staked out in the 2020 primary. And they just read it as: We want to win=
 this thing. And that sort goes for the Walz pick, too.

You put your finger on something important, which is that she=E2=80=99s jus=
t radiating this desire to win. So how do you win? One path revolves around=
 keeping the Democratic Party revved up, not factionalized. Basically, =E2=
=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s not do anything to lose this momentum.=E2=80=9D And the=
 other
would have been, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m willing to risk a certain amount of t=
hat in order to have that little extra edge in Pennsylvania,=E2=80=9D which=
 would have made Shapiro the obvious choice. They=E2=80=99re both valid per=
spectives. She clearly picked the enthusiasm vibe road, rather than what I =
would call the consultant class road.

=E2=80=9CDo No Harm=E2=80=9D

What is your understanding of how this pick came about?

First and foremost, they compressed a months-long process into a few days, =
and Eric Holder is really good. But as we both know, it=E2=80=99s easy to m=
iss things even with candidates who=E2=80=99ve been through vetting process=
es. And when you=E2=80=99re going this fast, you=E2=80=99re worried about t=
hat, because that=E2=80=99s the problem with people who don=E2=80=99t have =
a big national profile, like Tim Walz. If you=E2=80=99re in a hurry, you=E2=
=80=99re like, =E2=80=9CAre you guys sure you got everything? I=E2=80=99m a=
bout to put this guy on the ticket.=E2=80=9D I think there was a frame arou=
nd this decision, which was that the Democratic Party has just been through=
 more drama than you would normally get in 10 presidential cycles in the co=
urse of the last six weeks.

Part of the reason that Harris became the
nominee was because once Biden decided to step aside, after all that hearta=
che and agita and angst, the feeling was: We can=E2=80=99t go through more =
of this bullshit, fuck this mini primary bullshit, let=E2=80=99s just get b=
ehind the logical number two. And I think that carried over into this selec=
tion process, which was that nobody=E2=80=99s in the mood for outside-the-b=
ox drama. All of these candidates were good. If you looked at it purely in =
terms of who=E2=80=99s the best political athlete, Pete Buttigieg is easily=
 the best political athlete in the party. But he was never going to be the =
nominee. He might have been great if the J.D. Vance debate is going to cons=
ume somewhere between five and 15 days of news cycles, because the media=E2=
=80=99s obsessed with Vance and it=E2=80=99d be like Ali-Foreman, right? Bu=
t Pete was never going to be on the ticket. I can=E2=80=99t say anyone said=
 these words directly to me, but with the first Black woman in hailing dist=
ance of the Oval
Office, that is enough change.

I think the question you might be driving at here is, on Friday of last wee=
k, the political-journalistic establishment was saying it was likely to be =
Shapiro. He was the shortest on the shortlist. They were like, =E2=80=9CThi=
s is done.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t know where that came from, and I didn=
=E2=80=99t think that was true. But they really came down hard on that, and=
 it set up the weekend of attacks from different quarters who tried to take=
 Shapiro out, including by people that I find kind of incredible. I know Sh=
apiro is a rival of John Fetterman=E2=80=99s, but who does that to the gove=
rnor of your state when you=E2=80=99re in the Senate? Who turns around and =
openly knifes him ( https://www.politico.com/news/2024/08/03/fetterman-shap=
iro-harris-vp-00172557?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%288%2F7%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%287%2F24%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_t=
erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), not in the back, but in the front?
But that all happened, and today she ended up picking Tim Walz.

The big question, which I do not know the answer to, is whether she started=
 to see how much opposition Shapiro was generating and was like, =E2=80=9CI=
 don=E2=80=99t want this fight. I don=E2=80=99t want to risk a messy conven=
tion.=E2=80=9D Clearly they fed the narrative that it was going to be Shapi=
ro, or they didn=E2=80=99t effectively corral the narrative that it was goi=
ng to be Shapiro. That thing got out of the barn on Friday, and there are p=
eople in the filter, as we sometimes refer to our colleagues in the press, =
who have the view that she has a hard time making tough decisions. And this=
 will reinforce that narrative among some of our colleagues if they become =
convinced that she got rolled by the left.

I don=E2=80=99t know if
Walz wants to be president one day, but you do get that sense with Shapiro.

He wants to be president. Of course.

Kamala Harris understands that dynamic and how it plays out in the White Ho=
use. And to her credit, she has been very loyal to Joe Biden and didn=E2=80=
=99t want there to be a lot of friction, as much as she wanted to be presid=
ent one day. You get the sense that Walz doesn=E2=80=99t reek of the same a=
mbition as Shapiro.

This feeds into the line Fetterman was putting out there about his fellow K=
eystone Stater=E2=80=94that Shapiro was nakedly ambitious, which of course =
is hilarious coming from any politician. There=E2=80=99s no doubt that ther=
e=E2=80=99s more of an Obama/Biden vibe here than a Clinton/Gore vibe. Clin=
ton=E2=80=99s level of confidence that Al Gore was no threat to him was off=
 the charts. In Obama=E2=80=99s case, he was trying to compensate for thing=
s, like, =E2=80=9CI want someone who has Capitol Hill experience, I want a =
gray head of hair,
I want someone who knows about foreign policy.=E2=80=9D Both legitimate str=
ategic choices, both worked.

It raises the question: What exactly are you worried about? Your vice presi=
dent is going to usurp you, is going to primary you? You=E2=80=99re the pre=
sident of the United States! We know what happens with vice presidents afte=
r the campaign is over. If Tim Walz becomes the vice president, and whether=
 he helps her or not electorally in any quantifiable way, he will be shoved=
 into a broom closet in the Old Executive Office Building, and we=E2=80=99l=
l read stories for the next two years about how Harris hates him, they don=
=E2=80=99t ever talk, he gets all the shitty assignments. I find it weird t=
o think that Harris would be scared that Shapiro would be a usurper of some=
 kind. I will say, the speech he gave Tuesday night was fucking killer. Any=
body who was in the Shapiro camp will have watched that speech and been lik=
e, =E2=80=9CMan, that would have been a good idea.=E2=80=9D

I think, right
now, people would say J.D. Vance is probably a net negative. Is this pick g=
oing to matter more? Because Kamala Harris is something of an empty vessel =
on the policy front, and she has to assuage skeptical voters that she=E2=80=
=99s not a San Francisco radical who=E2=80=99s going to open the borders an=
d empty the prisons.

I think running mates matter a lot in one sense only: It=E2=80=99s the firs=
t big decision that you make as the nominee before you get to the Oval Offi=
ce, and so the pick is a reflection of the person who made it. You=E2=80=99=
ve got to live with it, and it always tells you something about the nominee=
=2E And that=E2=80=99s why the main criter=
ia is always, Are you picking someb=
ody who=E2=80=99s ready to be president on day one? Dick Cheney? Oh, okay. =
Al Gore, Oh, okay. Joe Biden, okay. Even Mike Pence, that=E2=80=99s someone=
 who could be ready to be president. Check the box. Move on.

Now, if you make a choice that voters decide is irresponsible, it
can hurt you. The basic rule is, always do no harm. When you pick someone w=
ho becomes the story, that=E2=80=99s not good. In McCain=E2=80=99s case, it=
 was, Wait a minute, you=E2=80=99re old and you=E2=80=99ve had cancer three=
 times. Your actuarial table suggests there=E2=80=99s a reasonable chance, =
Senator McCain, that you will die in office, and you picked a woman who was=
 the mayor of Wasilla, Alaska until the day before yesterday. Are you fucki=
ng kidding? And then she starts talking about how she can see Alaska from h=
er house and she doesn=E2=80=99t read any newspapers.

In the end, are we going to look back and say, What was the Walz factor tha=
t got her over this or that finish line? The whole thing=E2=80=99s very pre=
carious, man. I really sympathize with her. If I were her, I=E2=80=99d be l=
ike, =E2=80=9CI do not want to have a bunch of fucking protests in Chicago.=
 I do not need that shit.=E2=80=9D

