x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b><i>Peter Hamby</=
i>: John, I have to ask you, and you have to be honest with me: How familia=
r were you with Tim Walz before two weeks ago?</b><br/><br/><i>John Heilema=
nn</i>: I was just on television with former senator <b>Claire</b> <b>McCas=
kill</b>, who said, =E2=80=9CI wasn=E2=80=99t really very familiar with him=
,=E2=80=9D which is Claire=E2=80=99s way of saying, =E2=80=9CI had no idea =
who he was.=E2=80=9D And Claire is pretty well-versed. Walz is a six-term c=
ongressman from Minnesota, and now governor, and the main national story he=
 was ever at the center of=E2=80=94and he wasn=E2=80=99t even at the <i>cen=
ter</i> of it=E2=80=94was the <b>George Floyd</b> story. So I=E2=80=99m jus=
t like Claire McCaskill: I knew who he was, I could have picked him out of =
a lineup, but if you=E2=80=99d asked me to rate his political athleticism, =
I would have been like, =E2=80=9CSorry, I haven=E2=80=99t seen enough to
know.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/><b>He genuinely came out of nowhere. It=E2=80=99s i=
nteresting to see people from the Midwest and from Minnesota who know him, =
or who claim to know him, being like, =E2=80=9CNow the world gets to see wh=
at we=E2=80=99ve all known!=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m like, How the hell did we =
miss this? He was on Capitol Hill for so long. </b><br/><br/>Someone I know=
 sent me an email=E2=80=94someone who=E2=80=99s not famous, but a <i>name</=
i> in the last 30 years in Democratic circles in Washington=E2=80=94and she=
 said Walz had been her dark horse candidate. And she went on to say, =E2=
=80=9CBecause my nephew ran twice for his seat in Minnesota and I got to se=
e him in action.=E2=80=9D She always thought he would be perfect for this. =
So there are people in the Midwest who do have this view. I bet if we had <=
b>Amy</b> <b>Klobuchar</b> on here, she would tell you Tim Walz stories til=
l the cows came home. But for me, it was really a jolt to the solar plexus.=
 <br/><br/>What got me was, on one of his early hits on <i>Morning Joe</i>,=
 he was
riffing on why <b>J.D. Vance</b> didn=E2=80=99t know rural America, and he =
said, =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know, I got a lot of hillbilly nephews, and =
none of them went to Yale.=E2=80=9D And I thought that was a really good li=
ne, a good piece of political communication from a couple different angles.=
 His vernacular, that kind of Main Street America, and the way he deploys i=
t=E2=80=A6 just like <b>Hubert Humphrey</b>, the happy warrior, he=E2=80=99=
s smiling while he takes the truncheon out and applies it to your cranium, =
and next thing, you=E2=80=99re <i>out</i>. That=E2=80=99s a real skill. <br=
/><br/><b>It=E2=80=99s a powerful line to deploy, especially from a guy in =
a party currently ruled by college-educated voters. That=E2=80=99s the elec=
torate for Democrats in a lot of ways, along with Black voters. A lot of th=
e electeds, including someone who was passed over for the slot, Josh Shapir=
o, are lawyers who went to nice schools. And Walz is a public school kid=E2=
=80=94he went to school on the G.I. Bill, just like Vance. I think that=E2=
=80=99s one
reason they decided to pick him, because his framing against Vance plays we=
ll for them.</b><br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s 100 percent right. And not only as=
 a public school kid, but a public school <i>teacher</i>. My father=E2=80=
=99s family was from Wisconsin, my mother=E2=80=99s family was from the Upp=
er Peninsula of Michigan. If you=E2=80=99re in those worlds, a liberal libr=
arian or a liberal school teacher is a common trope. They=E2=80=99re not se=
en as <i>threatening</i> liberals. They=E2=80=99re not woke. So Walz is a v=
ery familiar figure, in the tradition of Republican progressivism in Wiscon=
sin, like <b>Robert La Follette</b>, before we got to the <b>Trump</b> era.=
 It was like, =E2=80=9COh, you know, he=E2=80=99s not really my cup of tea,=
 but he=E2=80=99s not trying to impose some woke ideology on my kids.=E2=80=
=9D He=E2=80=99s a throwback in that way. <br/><br/>I think part of the way=
 this pick works, in terms of the <i>internal</i> politics of the Democrati=
c Party, is that his policies are fine for <b>A.O.C.</b> or anybody on the =
Squad,
but he does not read <i>Squad</i> in the cultural sense in America. He read=
s like a guy you=E2=80=99d run into at Pep Boys when you=E2=80=99re buying =
a new muffler. And you=E2=80=99re like, =E2=80=9COh, does he know how to fi=
x my car?=E2=80=9D And that=E2=80=99s a good place to be.<br/><br/><b>And t=
hen there was the way the Democratic Party, the electeds, coalesced around =
him and came out=E2=80=94A.O.C. and Bernie and Terry McAuliffe and Joe Manc=
hin. One reason Democrats are excited about Kamala is that she seems like s=
he cares about winning, totally papering over all of her issues that she st=
aked out in the 2020 primary. And they just read it as: We want to win this=
 thing. And that sort goes for the Walz pick, too. </b><br/><br/>You put yo=
ur finger on something important, which is that she=E2=80=99s just radiatin=
g this desire to win. So how <i>do</i> you win? One path revolves around ke=
eping the Democratic Party revved up, not factionalized. Basically, =E2=80=
=9CLet=E2=80=99s not do anything to lose this momentum.=E2=80=9D And the ot=
her
would have been, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m willing to risk a certain amount of t=
hat in order to have that little extra edge in Pennsylvania,=E2=80=9D which=
 would have made Shapiro the obvious choice. They=E2=80=99re both valid per=
spectives. She clearly picked the enthusiasm vibe road, rather than what I =
would call the consultant class road.<br/></td>
